Patriot Day is the official day of reminiscence for the tragic events of 2001. On this day, we honor the memory of those who were killed in the September 11 attacks.

Although Patriot day is not observed as a public holiday, the national flag is flown at half-mast on all United States government buildings and establishments; individuals are encouraged to display flags on their homes and a moment of silence is observed at 8:46 AM.

post_text:
We apologize. Last evening we shared a message to all of our stakeholders with reminders about how to stop the spread of COVID-19. Unfortunately, that message led to some confusion. We wish to provide clarification for those individuals awaiting results from a COVID test.

Clarification: Individuals waiting for the results of a COVID test, are advised to remain home until symptom free for at least 24 hours or until the test results are confirmed negative, whichever occurs first. When returning to school or work, adhere to social distancing and wear a face covering.

‚Ä¢ Remember, if you do not feel well - stay home.
‚Ä¢ If you seek medical attention, follow the direction or guidance of your health care provider.

Thank you.

post_text:
Important health reminder from Hernando Schools. In order to protect staff, students and families from exposure to COVID- 19, we remind everyone that if you are unwell - stay home. Individuals waiting for the results of a COVID test, must remain at home until those test results are confirmed negative. Finally, if you are directed by a health care provider or the Dept of Health to isolate or quarantine - it is vital that you follow those directions to limit exposure of others to the virus.

By adhering to routines of social distancing, hand washing and using face coverings we can all contribute to keeping ourselves and others healthy.

Thank you for your cooperation and stay well!

UPDATE 8.31.20 10:30 AM - Please check the email address on record for the parent/guardian's as well as the Skyward email for the links.

UPDATE 8-31-2020 7:42 AM : There was an unspecified error in the Microsoft Teams platform that affected the automatic enrollment of students in classes. The district has restarted the process and is working with Microsoft however there is no ETA on completion. Teachers will be emailing their students with a process to manually add them to the proper classes. We appreciate everyone's continued patience.

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: The Florida Department of Education APPROVES the #HernandoSchools Reopening Plan. Read the full media release on our website here, https://tinyurl.com/y53d4qxt
View the approved plan here, https://tinyurl.com/yxrtferw
"Our Reopening Plan is comprehensive. It was vital that we develop a deliberate, thoughtful and straightforward blueprint for the safety and well being of staff, students and for all of those who engage with us. Establishing a system of procedures and safeguards to ensure a safe reopening was vital work and, at no time, did our team lose sight of the value of that work,‚Äù Superintendent John Stratton said."
text:

shared_text:
Hernando County Sheriff's Office
August 4 at 12:49 PM ¬∑

August is Child Safety Awareness Month

Motorists are reminded to drive safely with and around children as the school year begins.

In 2019, there were 127,285 children age 0 to 17 involved in a crash in Florida resulting in 1,361 serious bodily injuries and 142 fatalities. As children travel to and from school or just biking around the neighborhood, motorists must ensure they arrive safely by obeying school zone speed limits, remaining attentive around child pedestrians and bicyclists, and properly stopping for school buses. Starting January 1, 2021, the penalties for passing a school bus will be doubled. It is imperative that all motorists properly stop for school buses so all of Florida‚Äôs children can arrive at school or home safely.

post_text:
#HernandoSchools ANNOUNCES DELAY OF FALL SPORTS:
You can read the full media release on our website.
"Today, the Hernando School District announced the decision to postpone the start of their fall sports, indefinitely, due to coronavirus. Citing recommendations made in a July 19th report, provided by the FHSAA Sports Medicine Advisory Committee (SMAC), the district based their decision to delay the start of fall athletics until the community shows a ‚ÄúDownward trajectory of positive tests‚Ä¶‚Äù as supported in the report. District officials will monitor data, provided by the Department of Health, to determine when football, volleyball, cross country, golf, swimming and cheerleading may begin their season. When public health benchmarks are met, schools in Hernando are likely to hold in-conference games only. A conference schedule will be developed if the season starts without a lengthy delay. At this time, student athletes in Hernando may continue with voluntary conditioning with all district health safeguards and procedures in place."

Information sharing from the Florida Department of Health: According to Florida Statute children must be properly immunized before registering or attending school. Back to school Immunizations will be available from and on location at the Health Department for no cost.
If your child is entering KG or going into 7th grade, your child may need vaccines. In order to keep our community safe during this pandemic as well as maintaining social distancing guidelines, effective June 1, 2020, an appointment will be necessary. Please schedule now to avoid lengthy wait times as appointment slots will be taken quickly. Call 352 540-6800 to schedule your appointment at the Department of Health, or contact your pediatrician.

Hernando Adult Ed
June 28 at 6:26 PM ¬∑

Everyone meet Steven. He graduated from SunTech‚Äôs Welding program in December 2019.

As an army veteran who served four years, he said that being able to utilize the GI Bill really helped him commit to the time.
Our evening class schedule worked well with his day job and the cost of the program was relatively inexpensive compared to some welding schools. Affordability is a huge motivator!

Steven says he achieved all this learning goals throughout the course - and that his instructor was very knowledgeable. The small cohort classes really helped build a great experience, and having employers come to class to visit really opened up the opportunities available in the field.

Want to know more about our Welding program please call 352-797-7018. Classes begin July 27th!

According to Florida Statute children must be properly immunized before registering or attending school. Back to school Immunizations will be available from and on location at the Health Department for no cost.
If your child is entering Kindergarten or going into 7th grade, your child may need vaccines. In order to keep our community safe during this pandemic as well as maintaining social distancing guidelines, effective June 1, 2020, an appointment will be necessary. Please schedule now to avoid lengthy wait times as appointment slots will be taken quickly. Call 352 540-6800 to schedule your appointment at the Department of Health, or contact your pediatrician.

Everyone meet former SunTech HVAC Graduate Jake Adlao of Kold Pro Air Conditioning & Refrigeration.

Jake has a Bachelors in Accountanting and worked in the bank for almost a decade in the Philippines. Coming to America in 2006, Jake had his share of challenges. He tried odd jobs from working as a dishwasher, janitor, factory worker (He assembled those 3D Glasses), sales associate, cafeteria assistant, Physical therapy aide and HVAC technician.

So why make the jump from Accounting to HVAC contractor you may ask. This is what he had to say...

‚ÄúI realized after working for someone in HVAC, that this is something that I can do. This is a well-compensated industry, that you can literally practice anywhere in the United States. And who does not need AC in Florida, right?
Making a career change is not easy but it is not impossible.‚Äù
-Jake Adlao
SunTech HVAC Graduate

Please check out his business page ü§ó üëáüèº
Kold Pro Air Conditioning & Refrigeration on Google!

post_text: To our parents and students, we all recognize that the 2019-2020 school year ended in a most unexpected way. We found ourselves moving quickly to reduce the potential health threat to our students and staff and the shift to online learning required quite an adjustment for our students, parents and our teachers. In a profession that is accustomed to a slow and steady approach to learning, we felt this year, our typical way of evaluating student gains may need further consideration. Working in close partnership with our teachers, we added a step to our normal calculation of final grades. Our goal was to ensure students were buffered against an extreme academic decline because of their 4th quarter grade. This graphic shows the basics of the calculation. Essentially, final grades will be determined using two different calculations. The student will be awarded the higher of the two. In most cases, the difference is small but we believe our students deserve the benefit of this consideration. Thank you, #HernandoSchools #HernandoStrong

We look forward to the great things you will do. You are #ForeverFierce! #5thgradegraduation #graduatingclassof2027

Thank you to 808 Island Treats for providing a cool treat to our 5th graders! What a great way to help everyone cool down and celebrate their achievements!

shared_text:
National Marine Educators Association
May 27 at 2:30 PM ¬∑

Join educators from the Bermuda Aquarium, Museum and Zoo, BUEI (Bermuda Underwater Exploration Institute), and BIOS-Bermuda Institute of Ocean Sciences for the first "Ocean Diaries."

This virtual education series will bring the unique experiences of ocean explorers to Bermuda and beyond, allowing students to connect with researchers to learn more about their careers, as well as the challenges they face while studying our blue planet.
The first episode, "The More You Know, the More You Realize You Don't Know" will feature Zoleka Filander, a benthic ecologist with the Department of Environment, Forestry, and Fisheries in South Africa.

Join us on Thursday, May 28, 2020 at 10:30am (UTC-3) on this Facebook Live event on the Bermuda Aquarium, Museum and Zoo Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/bermudaaquariummuseumandzoo
.
Submit your questions via Facebook during the event!

FUNDRAISER FOR VETERANS - Veterans HEAT Factory is a 501c (3) non-profit organization here in Hernando county dedicated to helping veterans and first responders who are struggling with Post Traumatic Stress and their families. This all-encompassing program helps these heroes with anxiety, depression, career and educational goals, family relationships and physical health. This non-profit is holding the following fundraising event.

Open now through May 15 they are having a virtual Pampered Chef party. A portion of the proceeds will go towards Veterans HEAT Factory. Please join us and find out all about these unique and useful products, learn some great cooking tips and recipes.
FUNDRAISER LINK: https://tinyurl.com/y8juxloq

Find out more about Veterans HEAT Factory here - https://www.veteransheatfactory.com/

In honor of Teacher Appreciation Week, a drive-thru celebration was held for the teachers today. A boxed lunch from Chick-Fil-A and other tokens of appreciation were given to the teachers. We wanted to let our teachers know how much we appreciate all their hard work at the school, including all the early mornings, late nights and weekends spent grading and preparing lesson plans. Our teachers are amazing role models to our students and make a positive impact on each student. There are not enough words to thank them for all that they do for our school and students! We truly appreciate and miss them very much!

post_text: #HernandoSchools #MentalHealthMay2020 #MentalHealthMatters #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth
shared_text:
MHANATIONAL.ORG
Owning Your Feelings

HCSD Student Services
May 7 at 3:58 PM ¬∑

Today is #ChildrensMentalHealthAwarenessDay! It can be easy to get caught up in our emotions. But, when we take time to really identify what we are feeling it can help us to better cope with challenging situations. Learn more here: https://www.mhanational.org/owning-your-feelings
* Fast Facts *
- The English language has over 3,000 words for emotions.
- When school-aged kids are taught about emotions for 20-30 minutes per week, their social behavior and school performance improves.
#MentalHealthMay2020 #MentalHealthMatters #HCSDStudentServices #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth
